Good question 👍
Most Ruby developers almost never use putc, so it’s good you're asking why it even exists.

🔹 What putc Does
putc "hello"
putc "world"

Output:

hw

Why?

Because:

putc prints only one character

It prints the first character of the argument

It does NOT add a newline

So:

putc "hello"   # prints "h"
putc "world"   # prints "w"
🔥 So What Is The Use?

putc is a low-level character output method.

It is useful when you want to:

1️⃣ Print character-by-character

Example:

str = "hello"

str.each_char do |ch|
  putc ch
end

Output:

hello
2️⃣ Work with ASCII / byte-level output
putc 65

Output:

A

Because 65 is ASCII for 'A'.

This is useful when:

Generating binary data

Working with file streams

Building low-level output formats

Custom encoders

3️⃣ Writing to a specific IO stream

You can use it with $stdout, files, etc.

File.open("test.txt", "w") do |f|
  f.putc "A"
end

This writes a single character to a file.

🔹 Why Not Just Use print?

Because:

print prints the entire string

putc prints exactly one character

putc works directly with bytes

It gives more control.

🔹 Real-world usage frequency

| Method  | Usage Frequency          |
| ------- | ------------------------ |
| `puts`  | 🔥 Very common           |
| `print` | Common                   |
| `p`     | Very common (debugging)  |
| `putc`  | Rare (low-level IO work) |

Most Rails developers never use putc.

🎯 Simple Interview Answer

putc prints a single character (or ASCII value) to the output stream without adding a newline. It is mainly used for low-level, character-by-character output or byte-level operations.

